1 vulnerability assessment under described in subsection (3), or
2 conduct a review of the statewide school safety information policy
3 described under in subsection (4), as applicable.
4 (2) Subject to subsection (3), not later than January 1, 2020,
5 a school district, intermediate school district, or public school
6 academy, or nonpublic school shall develop and adopt, and by not
7 later than July 1, 2026 and every 3 school years thereafter, a
8 school district, intermediate school district, or public school
9 academy shall update, with input from the public, an emergency
10 operations plan for each school building operated by the school
11 district, intermediate school district, or public school academy.
12 with input from the public. By not later than July 1, 2026 and
13 every 3 school years thereafter, a nonpublic school shall update
14 the emergency operations plan for each school building operated by
15 the nonpublic school. The board of the a school district or
16 intermediate school district or the board of directors of the a
17 public school academy shall adopt the emergency operations plan by
18 a majority vote of the members serving on the board or board of
19 directors at a public meeting of the board or board of directors
20 held in compliance with the open meetings act, 1976 PA 267, MCL
21 15.261 to 15.275.
22 (3) The emergency operations plan developed and adopted or
23 updated under subsection (2) must include guidelines and procedures
24 that address at least all of the following:
25 (a) School violence and attacks.
26 (b) Threats of school violence and attacks.
27 (c) Bomb threats.
28 (d) Fire.
29 (e) Weather-related emergencies.
CRM H00215'25 (H-2) f9sdr1

3
1 (f) Intruders.
2 (g) Parent and pupil reunification.
3 (h) Threats to a school-sponsored activity or event whether or
4 not it is held on school premises.
5 (i) A plan to train teachers on mental health and pupil and
6 teacher safety.
7 (j) A plan to improve school building security.
8 (k) An active violence protocol.
9 (l) Continuity of operations after an incident.
10 (m) A vulnerability assessment.
11 (n) The installation and use of the temporary locking devices
12 or systems described in section 1d of 1937 PA 306, MCL 388.851d, if
13 applicable.
14 (4) A school district, intermediate school district, or public
15 school academy that adopts and implements a statewide school safety
16 information policy under section 1308 that meets the requirements
17 under subsection (3) is in compliance with subsection (2).
18 (5) A school district, intermediate school district, or public
19 school academy, or nonpublic school shall provide notice to the
20 department of a completed emergency operations plan review under
21 subsection (1) by not later than 30 days after the completion of
22 the review, in a form and manner prescribed by the department. A
23 school district, intermediate school district, or public school
24 academy, or nonpublic school shall also provide notice to the
25 department of the adoption or update of an emergency operations
26 plan under subsection (2) by not later than 30 days after the
27 adoption or update of the emergency operations plan, in a form and
28 manner prescribed by the department.
29 (6) At least annually, the department shall provide to the
CRM H00215'25 (H-2) f9sdr1

4
1 office of school safety within the department of state police a
2 list of each school district, intermediate school district, or
3 public school academy, or nonpublic school that has not developed
4 and adopted or updated an emergency operations plan under
5 subsection (2).
6 (7) The office of school safety within the department of state
7 police shall coordinate with a law enforcement agency that has
8 jurisdiction over a school district, intermediate school district,
9 or public school academy, or nonpublic school that has not
10 developed and adopted or updated an emergency operations plan under
11 subsection (2) to notify the governing body of the school district,
12 intermediate school district, or public school academy, or
13 nonpublic school that the school district, intermediate school
14 district, or public school academy, or nonpublic school has not
15 developed and adopted or updated an emergency operations plan.
16 (8) An emergency operations plan developed and adopted or
17 updated under subsection (2), any information provided to the
18 department under subsection (5), and any information provided to
19 the office of school safety within the department of state police
20 under subsection (6) is confidential and is exempt from disclosure
21 under the freedom of information act, 1976 PA 442, MCL 15.231 to
22 15.246.
23 (9) By not later than July 1, 2026, the board of a school
24 district or intermediate school district, board of directors of a
25 public school academy, or governing body of a nonpublic school
26 shall ensure that each school operated by the board, board of
27 directors, or governing body has a school crisis team that is
28 responsible for handling a crisis in the event of a safety
29 incident. The school crisis team's responsibilities include, but
CRM H00215'25 (H-2) f9sdr1

5
1 are not limited to, initiating a lockdown procedure, assisting in
2 evacuation of pupils and staff from the school building, and
3 overseeing parent and pupil reunification. A school crisis team
4 described in this subsection must consist of at least the following
5 members:
6 (a) The principal of the school.
7 (b) The assistant principal of the school, if available.
8 (c) A school resource officer, if available.
9 (d) School safety or security personnel who work at or for the
10 public school or nonpublic school, if available.
11 (e) Any other appropriate school personnel.
12 (10) (9) As used in this section, "school building" means any
13 of the following:
14 (a) A building intended to be used to provide instruction for
15 pupils, including an addition to an existing building.
16 (b) A recreational or athletic structure or field intended to
17 be used by pupils.
